double b { 5.0 }; // 5.0 is a floating point literal (no suffix means double type by default)
float c { 5.0f }; // 5.0 is a floating point literal, f suffix means float type

int d { 0 };      // 0 is an integer
double e { 0.0 }; // 0.0 is a doubleNote that by default, floating point literals default to type double. Anfsuffix is used to denote a literal of type float.Best practiceAlways make sure the type of your literals match the type of the variables they’re being assigned to or used to initialize. Otherwise an unnecessary conversion will result, possibly with a loss of precision.Printing floating point numbersNow consider this simple program:#include <iostream>

int main()
{
